Characters are what drive the story. It is good to concentrate on them. From a certain perspective, the events of the story are important insofar as they tell us about the characters.

I too am guilty of delving far too deep into worldbuilding, taking vast amounts of notes about things just implied or never even mentioned in the scenes that come to me, building enormous collections of assumptions about the worlds in my head in which stories and scenes are set. I will admit I never went so far as to create an entire cosmology and an entire new fictional nuclear physics all the way down to detailed descriptions of the quark-equivalents that make up the local equivalent of subatomic particles, or a completely new mathematical model for a fictional universe's equivalent of gravity, but there but for the grace of God go I, amirite guise?

Anonymous Mon 16 Sep 2024 01:32:24 No.69190694 Report
Quoted By: >>69190829 >>69195540 >>69195821
>>69189810
Maybe I can a-splain this better. I'm using Stable Diffusion. Specifically I'm using SD 1.5, with the Automatic1111 front end/control system. There are threads on /trash/ where they go into deep deep technical detail about how this stuff works and how to use it, and I don't want to bore the thread to death, but there are a few different elements that are important to answering your question.

You describe the image you desire with a "prompt," which is normally a long string of adjectives and modifiers you hope the software recognizes. Writing a prompt is itself almost a dark art and some have likened it to learning a programming language, though I think that goes too far.

There are these files, normally enormous, several gigabytes in size, called "checkpoints." There are lots of them you can download. Some influence the style of the art in a certain way, like there are some you can install that are for making photorealistic images, or cartoony images that imitate a certain style. For waifur and waifur-adjacent stuff there is a certain group of checkpoints that were trained on the contents of e621 circa January 2023. These checkpoints recognize the image tags from those images as things you can specify in a prompt, within limitations. There usually have to have been at least roughly three hundred images with with a tag for it to be recognized, and the more images, the better, for quality, usually, and the more likely it will be that it will recognize the tag and create something where that tag is recognizable. It does recognize artist tags from e6, though certanly not all of them, or even most of them, just the ones where the tag was present at least three hundred-ish times. It does know Hladilnik's style, and a lot of others, from Baron Engel to Dimwitdog to Waspsalad, and it can emulate them recognizably.

Here, for example, is the result of the same prompt as for the sergal, except changed to be Peepor. I had to train a LoRA for her.

Stable Diffusion has the "img2img" tool that can, theoretically, do what you're describing, but you have to play with the settings a lot, and run off a big batch to pick out one or two that are good.

I thought ControlNet was for setting up poses that the AI can work around. To use a stick figure doodle as a starting point, I thought that was what img2img did. Img2img does require you to put in a prompt describing what you want your doodle to become. Anonymous Mon 16 Sep 2024 05:51:52 No.69196249 Report
Quoted By: >>69196315 >>69197098
>>69196085
Glad to be of service. There are a couple more things you need to know. Stable Diffusion is free to download, but getting it running can be very challenging. You have to have one of a very small, narrow subset of versions of a programming language called Python installed. Stable Diffusion is also very hardware-intensive. Specifically it is written to run on the graphics card rather than the CPU by default. It is very difficult to get anything usable in a reasonable amount of time out of a graphics card that has less than 8GB of memory. Also SD is written specifically for graphics cards with fairly recent nVidia chipsets. It can be made to work on Intel and AMD graphics cards but it is much more difficult to get running and it will be much slower, all else being approximately equal. Also I run SD in Linux. Some people can get it working okay in Windows, if that's what you're running, but a lot seems to depend on exactly which version of Windows you have installed. Some versions of Windows won't let you install Python, for example, not because it's some kind of retarded security feature, but because they don't include certain DLL files that the Python installer needs. Etc., etc., etc.

Also Stable Diffusion isn't very good with text.

>>69197098
>they reinvented DLL hell so you just waste loads of disc space
To be fair, the alternative that is Linux's shared dependencies has the issue where if one program demands one version of the dependency and another requires a different one there's no way to compromise. Funnily enough the Linux community has begrudgingly admitted that Windows' method of standalone DLL's for every program was the better approach by coming up with Flatpak, you compromise disk space for the sake of your software just working, where the latter is obviously more important if you're not some Gentoo autist running off of a 20GB HDD on a 15 year old machine which would be the only scenario where disk space conservation would be that much of an issue. And let's be honest, on a long enough timeline every Linux distro will waste disk space since no package manager can reliably uninstall unused dependencies.
